  "prompt": "Those Indian secular who support for Kashmir referendum, why not support for 'Hindu Rashtra'?",
  "response": "People who advocate for a referendum in Kashmir may do so based on principles they believe in, such as self-determination, human rights, or resolving long-standing geopolitical conflicts. However, support for Hindu Rashtra entails the concept of establishing India as a nation primarily for Hindus, which inherently contradicts the secular and pluralistic principles enshrined in the Indian Constitution.\n\nThe Indian Constitution guarantees equality and secularism, ensuring that all citizens of India, irrespective of their religion, have equal rights and opportunities. Advocating for Hindu Rashtra would undermine these constitutional principles and could lead to marginalization and discrimination against non-Hindu communities.\n\nSecular individuals might argue that the strength of India lies in its multiculturalism and diversity, and thus, it is essential to maintain and promote these values. Supporting Kashmir's referendum could be seen as a way to uphold the right to self-determination in a situation viewed as a disputed territory, whereas advocating for Hindu Rashtra goes against the foundational ideals of inclusive governance and religious neutrality in India.\n\nUltimately, views and opinions on these matters are highly subjective, influenced by various socio-political contexts and personal beliefs.",
